WEBVTT

00:01:56.686 --> 00:02:00.336
For example, if you stood up right now
and emptied the contents of your bag

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:01.556
all over the floor.

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:05.507
Perhaps you experienced one of those odd,
untranslatable emotions

00:02:05.531 --> 00:02:08.316
for which there's no obvious
English equivalent.

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:11.625
You might have felt the feeling
the Dutch called "gezelligheid,"

00:02:11.649 --> 00:02:15.781
being cozy and warm inside with friends
when it's cold and damp outside.

00:02:16.273 --> 00:02:18.589
Maybe if you were really lucky,

00:02:18.613 --> 00:02:19.807
you felt this:

00:02:20.358 --> 00:02:21.705
"basorexia,"

00:02:21.729 --> 00:02:23.766
a sudden urge to kiss someone.

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:25.844
(Laughter)

00:02:26.799 --> 00:02:28.602
We live in an age

00:02:28.626 --> 00:02:32.810
when knowledge of emotions
is an extremely important commodity,